@page "/about"

<PageTitle>About - State Machine Experiments</PageTitle>

<div class="card">
    <h1>About This Application</h1>

    <h2>Purpose</h2>
    <p>
        This application demonstrates a production-ready state machine architecture for managing complex workflows.
        It showcases best practices for implementing state-driven business logic in .NET applications.
    </p>

    <h2>Technology Stack</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Blazor WebAssembly</strong> - Client-side web UI framework running in the browser</li>
        <li><strong>.NET 10.0</strong> - Latest .NET runtime with C# language features</li>
        <li><strong>Stateless Library</strong> - Hierarchical state machine library with async support</li>
        <li><strong>Entity Framework Core</strong> - In-memory database for case persistence</li>
        <li><strong>MailKit</strong> - SMTP email service integration</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>State Machine Pattern Benefits</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Type Safety</h3>
        <p>Enum-based states and triggers eliminate runtime errors from string mismatches.</p>

        <h3>Explicit Transitions</h3>
        <p>All valid state transitions are defined upfront, preventing invalid state changes.</p>

        <h3>Centralized Business Logic</h3>
        <p>Workflow logic is encapsulated in state machine configuration, not scattered across controllers.</p>

        <h3>Auditability</h3>
        <p>Every state transition is recorded in the database with timestamps and metadata.</p>

        <h3>Testability</h3>
        <p>State machines can be easily unit tested with mock services and validators.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Workflow Examples</h2>
    <div class="card">
        <h3>Informal LOD Process</h3>
        <p>Start → Member Reports → Initial Review → Determination → End</p>

        <h3>Formal LOD Process</h3>
        <p>Start → Member Reports → Initial Review → Medical Review → Determination → (Optional Appeal) → End</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Developer</h2>
    <p>This project demonstrates modern .NET development practices including:</p>
    <ul>
        <li>Clean architecture with separated concerns</li>
        <li>Dependency injection for testability</li>
        <li>Async/await patterns throughout</li>
        <li>Entity Framework Core for data access</li>
        <li>Comprehensive unit testing</li>
    </ul>
</div>
